        <h3 id="introduction">Introduction</h3>

        <p>
            When working with two collections, we can find the equality between them using LINQ <Highlight>SequenceEqual()</Highlight> method. The idea here is to find out 
            if two collections are equal or find values in one which is not in other or to find values in common. With <Highlight>SequenceEqual()</Highlight>, we can compare 
            two collections for Equality.
        </p>

        <p>
            LINQ <Highlight>SequenceEqual()</Highlight> is used to answer questions about collection such as
        </p>

        <ul>
            <li>Read lines from two files and compare like git difference</li>
            <li>Read data from two different table to check for equality</li>
            <li>Compare data in tables between different environments</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 id="primitive-types">Using LINQ Sequence Equal to compare primitive types</h3>

        <p>
            Primitive data types like <Highlight>int</Highlight>, <Highlight>decimal</Highlight>, <Highlight>string</Highlight>, etc can just
            compare the values against other value in the collection
        </p>

        <CodeSnippet CssClass="language-csharp">
List&lt;int&gt; list = new() { 1, 2, 3, 4, 5 };
List&lt;int&gt; anotherList = new() { 1, 2, 3, 4, 5 };

//Method Syntax
bool result = list
              .SequenceEqual(anotherList);
                    
//Query Syntax
bool result = (from number in list select number)
              .SequenceEqual(anotherList);
        </CodeSnippet>

        <DemoSnippet Title="LINQ SequenceEqual Clause Demo">
